                <head>11. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>According to the recollections of several U.S. officials, Nicaraguan President
                        <persName corresp="#p_SGA1">Somoza</persName> approached Colonel
                        <persName>Neil Mara</persName>, Assistant Military Aide to President
                        <persName corresp="#p_THS1">Truman</persName>, in early July 1952 with a
                    plan to overthrow <persName corresp="#p_AGJ1">Arbenz</persName>.
                        <persName>Mara</persName>’s report convinced <persName corresp="#p_THS1"
                        >Truman</persName>, who immediately authorized <gloss target="#t_CIA1"
                        >CIA</gloss> action without informing the Department of State. See
                        <persName>Gleijeses</persName>, <hi rend="italic">Shattered Hope</hi>, pages
                    239–240, and <persName>Richard H. Immerman</persName>, <hi rend="italic">The
                            <gloss target="#t_CIA1">CIA</gloss> in Guatemala: The Foreign Policy of
                        Intervention</hi>, pages 120 ff. See also <ref
                        target="frus1952-54v04#pg_1041">
                        <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1952–1954, volume IV, pages
                        1041</ref>–<ref target="frus1952-54v04#pg_1043">1043</ref>.</p>
                <p>Little documentation on the beginning of the operation was found. See <ref
                        target="#d13">Documents 13</ref>, <ref target="#d21">21</ref>, and <ref
                        target="#d22">22</ref>.</p>
            </div>
